<p>1918<br/>Sat. 12th Oct.<br/>Theatre Francais.<br/>Tonight's programme.<br/>"Le Colonel"<br/>in "m'frez 8 jours"<br/>Comedie Militaire<br/>Colonel d'Argemont.   Alcide Bernard<br/>Mdlle. d'Argemont&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kortia Litsckko<br/>Le Prefet    &hellip;.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  M. Mirbeau<br/>Mme la Prefete &hellip;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Roy Alexander<br/>Fricolin  &hellip;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  E. Lecointe<br/>Flamebeau &hellip;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  George Ducrocq.<br/>Le Lieutenant &hellip;.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Paul Darras.<br/>Tartempion   &hellip;<br/>Agathe   &hellip;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Rene Lesacher</p>
<p>A beautifully mounted triple, all acted together &amp; it went with a swing.   I was supposed to be a chic Parisienne of 30 &amp; Bernard &amp; Whitaker dressed (including the famous "confection" of the English Co. now disguised as a white &amp; sexe "Dolly Varden" chapeau)<br/>The doctor (the Italian) pronounced the result "tres elegante!"   Praise indeed!   Nearly had an accident.   Was entering when the hat caught in the damned portiere &amp; cocked over.   I sailed across to a providential mirror and then returned to be "received" by M. le Colonel.</p>
